    <div id=3D"s-lg-box-27405988-container" class=3D"s-lib-box-container">
        <div id=3D"s-lg-box-27405988" class=3D"s-lib-box s-lib-box-std">
                            <h2 class=3D"s-lib-box-title">
                    Two-Way ANOVA
                                    </h2>
                        <div id=3D"s-lg-box-collapse-27405988">
                <div class=3D"s-lib-box-content">
                    <div id=3D"s-lg-content-63535997" class=3D"  clearfix">
    <p><span style=3D"font-size:18px;"><span style=3D"font-family:Arial,Hel=
vetica,sans-serif;">The Two-Way ANOVA is similar to the One-Way ANOVA, but&=
nbsp;is used when comparing&nbsp;groups on two different categorical variab=
les (i.e. gender and level of education). The biggest difference between th=
e One-Way and the Two-Way ANOVA is that in a Two-Way ANOVA, you are interpr=
eting main effects&nbsp;<em>and&nbsp;</em>interaction effects.</span></span=
></p>

<ul>
	<li><span style=3D"font-size:18px;"><span style=3D"font-family:Arial,Helve=
tica,sans-serif;">Main effects - think of this like a <em>t</em>-test (if o=
nly two levels of the IV)&nbsp; or a One-Way ANOVA (if more than two levels=
)</span></span>

	<ul>
		<li><span style=3D"font-size:18px;"><span style=3D"font-family:Arial,Helv=
etica,sans-serif;">If we were only looking at gender as a factor, is there =
a significant difference?</span></span></li>
		<li><span style=3D"font-size:18px;"><span style=3D"font-family:Arial,Helv=
etica,sans-serif;">If we were only looking at level of education as a facto=
r, is there a significant difference?</span></span></li>
	</ul>
	</li>
	<li><span style=3D"font-size:18px;"><span style=3D"font-family:Arial,Helve=
tica,sans-serif;">Interaction effects - this looks at pairings of the level=
s of each IV to determine if the interaction of those variables leads to a =
significant difference</span></span>
	<ul>
		<li><span style=3D"font-size:18px;"><span style=3D"font-family:Arial,Helv=
etica,sans-serif;">Example: Males with a High School Diploma, Females with =
an Associate's Degree</span></span></li>
	</ul>
	</li>
</ul>

<p><span style=3D"font-size:18px;"><span style=3D"font-family:Arial,Helveti=
ca,sans-serif;"><strong>Assumptions</strong></span></span></p>

<ol>
	<li><span style=3D"font-size:18px;"><span style=3D"font-family:Arial,Helve=
tica,sans-serif;">One continuous (interval or ratio) dependent variable and=
 two categorical (nominal or ordinal) independent variables with&nbsp;two o=
r more levels.</span></span></li>
	<li><span style=3D"font-size:18px;"><span style=3D"font-family:Arial,Helve=
tica,sans-serif;">Independence of observations - usually evaluated based on=
 the research design - participants only belong in one group of each IV</sp=
an></span></li>
	<li><span style=3D"font-size:18px;"><span style=3D"font-family:Arial,Helve=
tica,sans-serif;">No significant outliers - can be assessed using boxplots,=
 scatterplots, and other methods</span></span></li>
	<li><span style=3D"font-size:18px;"><span style=3D"font-family:Arial,Helve=
tica,sans-serif;">The dependent variable is approximately normally distribu=
ted&nbsp;<em>for each combination&nbsp;</em>of the levels of the independen=
t variables</span></span></li>
	<li><span style=3D"font-size:18px;"><span style=3D"font-family:Arial,Helve=
tica,sans-serif;">Homogeneity of variances&nbsp;<em>for each combination</e=
m>&nbsp;of the levels of the independent variables</span></span></li>
</ol>

<p><span style=3D"font-size:18px;"><span style=3D"font-family:Arial,Helveti=
ca,sans-serif;"><strong>Running One-Way ANOVA&nbsp;in SPSS</strong></span><=
/span></p>

<ol>
	<li><span style=3D"font-size:18px;"><span style=3D"font-family:Arial,Helve=
tica,sans-serif;">Analyze &gt; General Linear Model&nbsp;&gt; Univariate</s=
pan></span></li>
	<li><span style=3D"font-size:18px;"><span style=3D"font-family:Arial,Helve=
tica,sans-serif;">Move the continuous variable into the "Dependent Variable=
" box and the categorical variables into the "Fixed Factor(s)" box</span></=
span></li>
	<li><span style=3D"font-size:18px;"><span style=3D"font-family:Arial,Helve=
tica,sans-serif;">Click on the Post Hoc button</span></span>
	<ul>
		<li><span style=3D"font-size:18px;"><span style=3D"font-family:Arial,Helv=
etica,sans-serif;">choose the appropriate post hoc analysis for your study<=
/span></span></li>
		<li><span style=3D"font-size:18px;"><span style=3D"font-family:Arial,Helv=
etica,sans-serif;">Select Continue</span></span></li>
	</ul>
	</li>
	<li><span style=3D"font-size:18px;"><span style=3D"font-family:Arial,Helve=
tica,sans-serif;">You may select additional output, such as descriptive sta=
tistics, using the Options button</span></span></li>
	<li><span style=3D"font-size:18px;"><span style=3D"font-family:Arial,Helve=
tica,sans-serif;">You may include univariate graphs using the Plots button<=
/span></span></li>
	<li><span style=3D"font-size:18px;"><span style=3D"font-family:Arial,Helve=
tica,sans-serif;">You may include estimated marginal means using the EM Mea=
ns button</span></span></li>
	<li><span style=3D"font-size:18px;"><span style=3D"font-family:Arial,Helve=
tica,sans-serif;">You can select your post hoc test(s) using the Post Hoc b=
utton</span></span></li>
	<li><span style=3D"font-size:18px;"><span style=3D"font-family:Arial,Helve=
tica,sans-serif;">Select OK to run the analysis</span></span></li>
</ol>

<p><span style=3D"font-size:18px;"><span style=3D"font-family:Arial,Helveti=
ca,sans-serif;"><strong>Interpreting the Output</strong></span></span></p>

<ul>
	<li><span style=3D"font-size:18px;"><span style=3D"font-family:Arial,Helve=
tica,sans-serif;">Descriptives (if you opted to include them)</span></span>

	<ul>
		<li><span style=3D"font-size:18px;"><span style=3D"font-family:Arial,Helv=
etica,sans-serif;">provides means and standard deviations&nbsp;based on com=
binations of&nbsp;levels of the IVs</span></span></li>
	</ul>
	</li>
	<li><span style=3D"font-size:18px;"><span style=3D"font-family:Arial,Helve=
tica,sans-serif;">Tests of Between-Subjects Effects</span></span>
	<ul>
		<li><span style=3D"font-size:18px;"><span style=3D"font-family:Arial,Helv=
etica,sans-serif;">Provides the results of the statistical tests</span></sp=
an>
		<ul>
			<li><span style=3D"font-size:18px;"><span style=3D"font-family:Arial,Hel=
vetica,sans-serif;">Main effects - look for your individual IVs (i.e. gende=
r and education level)</span></span>
			<ul>
				<li><span style=3D"font-size:18px;"><span style=3D"font-family:Arial,He=
lvetica,sans-serif;">test statistic =3D F-ratio</span></span></li>
				<li><span style=3D"font-size:18px;"><span style=3D"font-family:Arial,He=
lvetica,sans-serif;">associated probability =3D Sig.</span></span></li>
			</ul>
			</li>
			<li><span style=3D"font-size:18px;"><span style=3D"font-family:Arial,Hel=
vetica,sans-serif;">Interaction effects - look for the combination of your =
two IVs (i.e. gender*education level)</span></span>
			<ul>
				<li><span style=3D"font-size:18px;"><span style=3D"font-family:Arial,He=
lvetica,sans-serif;">test statistic =3D <em>F</em>-ratio</span></span></li>
				<li><span style=3D"font-size:18px;"><span style=3D"font-family:Arial,He=
lvetica,sans-serif;">associated probability - Sig.</span></span></li>
			</ul>
			</li>
		</ul>
		</li>
		<li><span style=3D"font-size:18px;"><span style=3D"font-family:Arial,Helv=
etica,sans-serif;">Used to make a decision about the null hypothesis</span>=
</span></li>
	</ul>
	</li>
	<li><span style=3D"font-size:18px;"><span style=3D"font-family:Arial,Helve=
tica,sans-serif;">Multiple Comparisons</span></span>
	<ul>
		<li><span style=3D"font-size:18px;"><span style=3D"font-family:Arial,Helv=
etica,sans-serif;">Provides the results of the post hoc analysis</span></sp=
an></li>
		<li><span style=3D"font-size:18px;"><span style=3D"font-family:Arial,Helv=
etica,sans-serif;">Allows you to determine exactly which groups are signifi=
cantly different than each other</span></span>
		<ul>
			<li><span style=3D"font-size:18px;"><span style=3D"font-family:Arial,Hel=
vetica,sans-serif;">compare the Sig. to your level of significance (i.e. .0=
5)</span></span></li>
		</ul>
		</li>
	</ul>
	</li>
</ul>

<p><span style=3D"font-size:18px;"><span style=3D"font-family:Arial,Helveti=
ca,sans-serif;"><strong>Reporting Results in APA Style</strong></span></spa=
n></p>

<p><span style=3D"font-size:18px;"><span style=3D"font-family:Arial,Helveti=
ca,sans-serif;">A Two-Way ANOVA was conducted to determine to what extent g=
ender and education level have an effect on income. There was a statistical=
ly significant interaction between the effects of gender and education leve=
l on income (<i>F</i>(2,37) =3D 5.21,&nbsp;<em>p</em>&nbsp;&lt; .01). Simpl=
e main effects analysis showed that females earned significantly lower inco=
mes than males when higher levels of education had been pursued (<em>p&nbsp=
;</em>=3D .003), but there was no difference noted with only high school (<=
em>p</em>&nbsp;=3D .42) or undergraduate levels of education (<em>p</em>&nb=
sp;=3D .19).</span></span></p>


    </div>
                </div>
               =20
